="Times New Roman"/><w:color w:val="000000"/></w:rPr><w:t>, Redmond, WA</w:t></w:r></w:p><w:p w14:paraId="2CF9C4D6" w14:textId="1A3A3914" w:rsidR="0006039E" w:rsidRPr="005F0604" w:rsidRDefault="00644A58" w:rsidP="00B23FBB"><w:pPr><w:spacing w:after="120" w:line="240" w:lineRule="auto"/><w:jc w:val="both"/><w:rPr><w:rFonts w:ascii="Times New Roman" w:eastAsia="Times New Roman" w:hAnsi="Times New Roman" w:cs="Times New Roman"/><w:color w:val="000000"/></w:rPr></w:pPr><w:r w:rsidRPr="005F0604"><w:rPr><w:rFonts w:ascii="Times New Roman" w:eastAsia="Times New Roman" w:hAnsi="Times New Roman" w:cs="Times New Roman"/><w:color w:val="000000"/><w:vertAlign w:val="superscript"/></w:rPr><w:t xml:space="preserve">c </w:t></w:r><w:r w:rsidRPr="005F0604"><w:rPr><w:rFonts w:ascii="Times New Roman" w:eastAsia="Times New Roman" w:hAnsi="Times New Roman" w:cs="Times New Roman"/><w:color w:val="000000"/></w:rPr><w:t>Division of Cardiology, University of Washington, Seattle, WA</w:t></w:r></w:p><w:p w14:paraId="2AEBA732" w14:textId="77777777" w:rsidR="000923B2" w:rsidRPr="005F0604" w:rsidRDefault="000923B2" w:rsidP="00B23FBB"><w:pPr><w:spacing w:after="120" w:line="240" w:lineRule="auto"/><w:jc w:val="both"/><w:rPr><w:rFonts w:ascii="Times New Roman" w:eastAsia="Times New Roman" w:hAnsi="Times New Roman" w:cs="Times New Roman"/><w:color w:val="000000"/></w:rPr></w:pPr><w:r w:rsidRPr="005F0604"><w:rPr><w:rFonts w:ascii="Times New Roman" w:eastAsia="Times New Roman" w:hAnsi="Times New Roman" w:cs="Times New Roman"/><w:color w:val="000000"/><w:vertAlign w:val="superscript"/></w:rPr><w:t xml:space="preserve">d </w:t></w:r><w:r w:rsidRPr="005F0604"><w:rPr><w:rFonts w:ascii="Times New Roman" w:eastAsia="Times New Roman" w:hAnsi="Times New Roman" w:cs="Times New Roman"/><w:color w:val="000000"/></w:rPr><w:t>Department of Psychiatry, F. E. Hébert School of Medicine, Uniformed Services University, Bethesda, MD</w:t></w:r></w:p><w:p w14:paraId="4E30844A" w14:textId="77777777" w:rsidR="0094056C" w:rsidRDefault="00DE4580" w:rsidP="00DE4580"><w:pPr><w:spacing w:after="0" w:line="240" w:lineRule="auto"/><w:jc w:val="both"/><w:rPr><w:rFonts w:ascii="Times New Roman" w:hAnsi="Times New Roman" w:cs="Times New Roman"/><w:bCs/></w:rPr></w:pPr><w:r w:rsidRPr="00DE4580"><w:rPr><w:rFonts w:ascii="Times New Roman" w:hAnsi="Times New Roman" w:cs="Times New Roman"/><w:bCs/></w:rPr><w:t>The glymphatic system clears metabolic waste during sleep, with slow-wave sleep (SWS) playing a central role. Standard sleep assessment tools &#x2014; electroencephalography (EEG) and polysomnography (PSG) &#x2014; capture neural and physiological activity but offer no direct window into brain fluid dynamics. Intracranial pressure (ICP), shaped by cerebral blood flow, cerebrospinal fluid circulation, and sleep-state transitions, is a potential source of complementary information. Here we ask whether a wearable sleep mask with capacitive temple sensors can detect ICP-related brain capacitance changes during sleep and, specifically, whether those signals carry spectral signatures of SWS. Six healthy adults (20&#x2013;60 years) each wore the mask on two consecutive nights (12 recordings). We extracted respiratory (RS) and heartbeat (HB) components from the capacitance signal and compared them against PSG-derived respiratory flow, ECG, and photoplethysmography (PPG). After per-session calibration, HB rate estimates reached a mean absolute error of 4.19 BPM &#x2014; a 77% reduction from the uncalibrated baseline &#x2014; while RS accuracy improved by roughly 25%. Calibration scaling factors were stable within subjects across nights but shifted with sleep stage, pointing to autonomic modulation of the capacitance signal. To look for SWS-specific features, we applied spectral ridge tracking to the time&#x2013;frequency representation of each recording. The algorithm identifies persistent narrow-band peaks in the spectrogram and links them over time into continuous ridges. Non-sinusoidal oscillations produce harmonic ladders &#x2014; a fundamental frequency plus integer multiples (2&#xD7;, 3&#xD7;) &#x2014; which appear as co-occurring ridges at harmonic ratios. In 58% of motion-artifact-free epochs we detected two or more harmonically related spectral peaks, and 44% of epochs contained persistent ridges. The longest individual ridges lasted up to 74 minutes; the median per-session maximum was 25 minutes. During PSG-confirmed N3, ridge power dropped roughly 40% relative to other stages (median 0.11 vs. 0.18) and fewer harmonic groups were active at the same time, consistent with the slower, more regular oscillations that dominate deep sleep. These ridge patterns were reproducible across the two nights for each subject. The spectral changes were also present in brain capacitance independently of thoracic respiratory signals, suggesting the mask picks up ICP-related dynamics beyond respiratory coupling alone.</w:t></w:r><w:r w:rsidRPr="00DE4580"><w:rPr><w:rFonts w:ascii="Times New Roman" w:hAnsi="Times New Roman" w:cs="Times New Roman"/><w:bCs/></w:rPr><w:t xml:space="preserve"> Together, these results show that capacitance signals recorded at the temple contain structured spectral features &#x2014; persistent ridges and harmonic ladders &#x2014; that track sleep stage and distinguish SWS. A wearable sleep mask based on this approach could offer a practical, noninvasive route for detecting slow-wave sleep and, potentially, for monitoring glymphatic-related physiology outside the sleep lab.</w:t></w:r></w:p><w:p w14:paraId="65EA3AE4" w14:textId="77777777" w:rsidR="001D1A90" w:rsidRDefault="001D1A90" w:rsidP="00DE4580"><w:pPr><w:spacing w:after="0" w:line="240" w:lineRule="auto"/><w:jc w:val="both"/><w:rPr><w:rFonts w:ascii="Times New Roman" w:hAnsi="Times New Roman" w:cs="Times New Roman"/><w:bCs/></w:rPr></w:pPr></w:p><w:p w14:paraId="5FF01F67" w14:textId="42158232" w:rsidR="00951380" w:rsidRPr="005F0604" w:rsidRDefault="00AE003B" w:rsidP="00DE4580"><w:pPr><w: